Cryptography is the math behind secure communication

Private Key
The private key is the most critical piece of secret data you own. Think of it as your unique signature stamp from our analogy. It is used to create a digital signature for any message, such as a transaction.
Function: To sign and authorize transactions.
Security: Your private key must be kept secret at all times. Never share it with anyone. If someone gains access to your private key, they gain complete control over your account and can sign transactions to steal your funds.

Public Key
The public key is derived from your private key and is safe to share with others. In our analogy, this is like your public mailbox address.
Function: To allow others to verify that a signature was created by the corresponding private key.
The One-Way Relationship: You can easily generate a public key from a private key, but it is computationally impossible to reverse the process and derive a private key from a public key. 
This one-way function is what makes public verification possible without compromising your security.
ECDSA - Signatures used to seal agreements like your own personal stamp

Private keys and public keys are mathematically signed together, it is a one way mathematical relationship your public key and be used to verify the pprivate key but it does not give access to your private key.
A public key is the wallet address but a wallet address is the shortened version or hashed version of the public key

The private key is going to be used to sign messages and prove ownership
A private key has to stay private else your account can be sccessed by someone else
Ethereum key is a shorted version of public key and it is derived from the public key it is still hashed but simpler


A seed phrase is used to generate private keys, it is a master key that can be used to create all keys for unlimited doors or unlimited accounts 
Function: All of your private keys are deterministically derived from this single phrase. If you lose access to your wallet, you can restore it on any device using only your seed phrase.
Security: Protecting your seed phrase is the single most important rule of wallet security. If someone gets your seed phrase, they have access to every account and all the funds within that wallet.

POS (Prof of Stake)
The security of a Proof of Stake network is not based on computational work but on a powerful economic model. The system operates on the assumption that at least two-thirds of the total staked value is controlled by honest actors who will follow the protocol's rules.
To enforce honesty, PoS introduces a severe penalty known as slashing.
How does proof of work attain finality?
Finality in Proof of Stake (PoS) is achieved through validator voting + economic penalties, rather than brute-force computation like in Proof of Work.

Slot vs Epoch
A slot is the smallest unit of time in Ethereum PoS.
1 slot = 12 seconds
In each slot:
One validator is chosen to propose a block
Other validators attest (vote) on it

What is an epoch?
An epoch is a group of slots.
1 epoch = 32 slots
Since each slot is 12 seconds:
1 epoch = 32 × 12 = 384 seconds
That’s 6 minutes 24 seconds
Epochs are important because:
Validator rewards/penalties are calculated per epoch
Finality decisions happen at epoch boundaries
Validator duties (who proposes, who attests) are reshuffled

